extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "Panel | Configuration"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 Panel configuration
				p.lead Options via constructor, data attributes, or both

	+section("Setting options")
		h3 JavaScript options

		+codeblock('JS').
			Panel.init({ axis: 'horizontal', closeOnResize: true });

			const panel = new Panel('#my-panel', {
				axis: 'vertical',
				transitions: true,
				autoFocus: 'first',
				returnFocus: true
			});

		h3 Data attributes

		+codeblock('HTML')
			#my-panel(data-panel data-panel-axis="horizontal" data-panel-close-on-resize data-panel-transitions="false")
				.panel-wrapper ...


		p When the same option is set more than one way, the most specific wins: #[strong defaults -&gt; JS options -&gt; group attribute -&gt; element attribute]. So a data attribute on one panel always beats a global #[code init()] option.

		p That is how one panel opts out of a flag the rest of the page opted into. With #[code Panel.init({ persist: true })] covering every panel, a single panel can still switch it off:

		+codeblock('HTML')
			// Persists (inherits the global init option)
			#saved(data-panel)
				.panel-wrapper ...
			+n
			// Opts out, even though init() set persist: true
			#not-saved(data-panel data-panel-persist="false")
				.panel-wrapper ...

		p For #[code persist] and #[code deepLink], a #[code data-panel-group] can set the option for every panel inside it at once. A panel’s own attribute still wins over the group’s.

		p On #[code &lt;ps-panel&gt;] (a web component) the same options are plain attributes: no #[code data-] prefix, no JS call (third card of each option below). There is no web-component equivalent of a global config object, because #[code connectedCallback] fires per element on its own, with no shared init moment. So for page-wide defaults across many elements, JS #[code init()] is the better tool. A web component can easily coexist with the regular JS version. Full examples on the #[a(href=url('/panel/examples/webcomponent.html')) Web Component integration] page.

	+section("Available options")
		p Every option below shows three ways to set it: a JS key, a data attribute, and a plain attribute for #[code &lt;ps-panel&gt;]. All three land on the same config, so pick whichever suits how you are authoring.

		.column.gap-1(data-panel-group data-panel-close-siblings)

			+apiOption("align: 'start' | 'center' | 'end'")

				p Where the content sits inside the clipped container while it animates. Handy for panels that reveal from the centre or the far edge.

				h4 Default: #[code 'start']
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { align: 'start' }]: content grows from the top / left edge
							li #[code { align: 'center' }]: content stays centered
							li #[code { align: 'end' }]: content grows from the bottom / right edge
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-align="start"]
							li #[code data-panel-align="center"]
							li #[code data-panel-align="end"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-align="start"]
							li #[code panel-align="center"]
							li #[code panel-align="end"]

			+apiOption("autoFocus: false | true | 'heading' | 'first' | 'input'")
				p Move focus into the panel when it opens, so a screen-reader user knows the content has changed.
				ul
					li #[code false]: no focus movement
					li #[code true]: focus the panel element itself
					li #[code 'heading']: focus the first h1-h6
					li #[code 'first']: focus the first focusable element (keyboard events only)
					li #[code 'input']: focus the first input/select/textarea (bypasses keyboard check)

				p Pass the original event to #[code open()] or #[code toggle()] and Panel tells keyboard from mouse: a mouse click skips autofocus, which keeps the page from jumping.

				h4 Default: #[code false]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { autoFocus: false }]
							li #[code { autoFocus: true }]
							li #[code { autoFocus: 'heading' }]
							li #[code { autoFocus: 'first' }]
							li #[code { autoFocus: 'input' }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-auto-focus="true"]
							li #[code data-panel-auto-focus="heading"]
							li #[code data-panel-auto-focus="first"]
							li #[code data-panel-auto-focus="input"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-auto-focus="true"]
							li #[code panel-auto-focus="heading"]
							li #[code panel-auto-focus="first"]
							li #[code panel-auto-focus="input"]

			+apiOption("axis: 'vertical' | 'horizontal'")
			
				p Which dimension animates: #[code vertical] grows the height, #[code horizontal] grows the width.

				h4 Default: #[code 'vertical']
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { axis: 'vertical' }]: show-more, accordions
							li #[code { axis: 'horizontal' }]: sidebars, drawers
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-axis="vertical"]
							li #[code data-panel-axis="horizontal"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-axis="vertical"]
							li #[code panel-axis="horizontal"]

			+apiOption("closeOnResize: boolean")
				p Close the panel when the window resizes. Useful for horizontal panels, whose surrounding layout can break at other viewport widths.

				h4 Default: #[code false]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { closeOnResize: true }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-close-on-resize]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-close-on-resize]

			+apiOption("closeSiblings: boolean")
				p When this panel opens, close any other open panel in the same #[code [data-panel-group]]. You can also set it on the group element with #[code data-panel-close-siblings].

				h4 Default: #[code false]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { closeSiblings: true }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-close-siblings]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-close-siblings]

				.callout 
					+warning()
					p #[strong Note]: when this is on, a closing sibling animates with the #[code --ps-open-speed] and #[code --ps-open-timing] variables, not its own close timing. That keeps the two movements in step instead of looking wobbly.

			+apiOption("debug: boolean")
				p Log open and close events to the console. Handy when something is opening that shouldn’t be, quiet otherwise.

				h4 Default: #[code false]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { debug: true }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-debug]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code debug]

			+apiOption("deepLink: boolean")

				p Keep the #[code ?panel=] URL param in sync as the panel opens and closes (via #[code history.replaceState], so no new history entries pile up). The address bar then always reflects the current state, ready to copy and share. Reading the param on load happens regardless: #[code deepLink] only decides whether opening and closing write back to it. Want shareable URLs and #[code localStorage] restore? Turn on #[code persist] and #[code deepLink] together.

				h4 Default: #[code false]

				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { deepLink: true }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-deeplink]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-deeplink]
				p The panel needs an #[code id], or there is nothing to put in the URL.

			+apiOption("interruptible: boolean")

				p Leave it on. With it off, any open or close that arrives mid-animation or mid-load is dropped, and the one already running finishes first.

				h4 Default: #[code true]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { interruptible: false }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-interruptible="false"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-interruptible="false"]

			+apiOption("loadingDelay: number")

				p How long to wait before showing the spinner while async content loads. It prevents spinner flash on fast connections.

				h4 Default: #[code 320]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { loadingDelay: 320 }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-loading-delay="320"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-loading-delay="320"]

			+apiOption("loadingHeight: number")
				p The height, in pixels, the panel holds while async content loads. Somewhere for the spinner to live until the real content turns up.

				h4 Default: #[code 150]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { loadingHeight: 200 }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-loading-height="200"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-loading-height="200"]

			+apiOption("persist: boolean")
				p Save the panel’s open or closed state to #[code localStorage] on every change, and restore it on the next load, so the panel comes back the way the user left it.

				p You can also set it on a #[code [data-panel-group]] to cover every direct panel in the group, instead of marking each one.

				h4 Default: #[code false]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { persist: true }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-persist]: on the panel element
							li #[code data-panel-persist]: on a #[code [data-panel-group]] element
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-persist]
				p The panel needs an #[code id], or there is nothing to key the storage on.

			+apiOption("returnFocus: boolean")
				p When the panel closes, send focus back to the trigger that opened it, so a keyboard user picks up where they were.

				h4 Default: #[code true]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { returnFocus: true }]
							li #[code { returnFocus: false }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-return-focus="false"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-return-focus="false"]

			+apiOption("transitions: boolean")
				p Turn the CSS size animation on or off.
				h4 Default: #[code true]
				.card-row
					.card
						h4 JavaScript
						ul
							li #[code { transitions: true }]
							li #[code { transitions: false }]
					.card
						h4 Data attribute
						ul
							li #[code data-panel-transitions="false"]
					.card
						h4 Web Component attribute
						ul
							li #[code panel-transitions="false"]

	+section("Grouping panels", "Grouping panels")

		p #[code data-panel-group] is just a scope marker. On its own it does nothing, but it is where the group-level options live (#[code data-panel-close-siblings], #[code data-panel-persist], #[code data-panel-deeplink]), and it gives you a handle to target the group in CSS.

		+codeblock('HTML')
			div(data-panel-group)
				h4
					button(aria-controls="acc-1" aria-expanded="false") Question 1
				#acc-1(data-panel)
					.panel-wrapper Answer 1
				h4
					button(aria-controls="acc-2" aria-expanded="false") Question 2
				+n
				#acc-2(data-panel)
					.panel-wrapper Answer 2


		p Add #[code data-panel-close-siblings] so opening one panel closes the rest. That is the line that turns a group into an accordion.

		+codeblock('HTML')
			div(data-panel-group data-panel-close-siblings)
				h4
					button(aria-controls="acc-1" aria-expanded="false") Question 1
				#acc-1(data-panel)
					.panel-wrapper Answer 1
				h4
					button(aria-controls="acc-2" aria-expanded="false") Question 2
				+n
				#acc-2(data-panel)
					.panel-wrapper Answer 2



		p Without #[code data-panel-close-siblings] the panels are independent: any number can be open at once. The group element can be any tag, and you can have as many separate groups on a page as you like.

	+section("Implicit trigger wiring", "Implicit wiring")
		p When a button sits right next to its panel in the markup, you can skip the #[code id] / #[code aria-controls] pairing altogether. Put #[code data-panel-trigger] on the button and Panel finds the next #[code [data-panel]] sibling, gives it a stable generated id, and wires up #[code aria-controls] and #[code aria-expanded] for you.

		+codeblock('HTML')
			button(data-panel-trigger) Toggle
			+n
			div(data-panel)
				.panel-wrapper Content

		p The #[code data-panel-trigger] button can also sit inside a heading. If it is a direct child of a heading (#[code h1]–#[code h6]) that is the panel’s sibling, Panel wires it the same way, which keeps an accordion’s heading markup clean:

		+codeblock('HTML')
			h3
				button(data-panel-trigger) Toggle
			+n
			div(data-panel)
				.panel-wrapper Content

		p This earns its keep on repeated collapse patterns (accordions, catalogues), where inventing a unique id for every item is pure boilerplate. The generated ids (#[code panel-1], #[code panel-2], and so on) stay stable for the life of the page load and count up in DOM order.

		p If the panel already has an #[code id], Panel leaves it alone. #[code data-panel-trigger] only comes up with one when it is missing.

	+section("Events")
		p Panel dispatches custom events on the panel element as it opens and closes. They all bubble, and each carries a #[code detail] object with a #[code trigger]: the element that started the action, or #[code null] when your script did it.

		.card
			table.table
				thead
					tr
						th Event
						th Fires when
				tbody
					tr
						td #[code panel:beforeopen]
						td
							p Before the open animation starts. Attach a #[code Promise] to #[code detail.promise] to defer opening until async content is ready. Also exposes #[code detail.signal] (aborted if the open is cancelled).
					tr
						td #[code panel:opening]
						td The open animation has started.
					tr
						td #[code panel:opened]
						td The open animation has finished.
					tr
						td #[code panel:closing]
						td The close animation has started.
					tr
						td #[code panel:closed]
						td The close animation has finished.

		+codeblock('JS').
			document.querySelector('#my-panel').addEventListener('panel:opened', e => {
				console.log('Opened by', e.detail.trigger);
			});

			// Async content loading
			document.querySelector('#my-panel').addEventListener('panel:beforeopen', e => {
				e.detail.promise = fetch('/content').then(r => r.text()).then(html => {
					e.currentTarget.querySelector('.panel-wrapper').innerHTML = html;
				});
			});

	+section("CSS variables")
		p Timing and look come from CSS custom properties, set on the element or any ancestor. Every duration needs a unit (#[code 0s], never a bare #[code 0], or the browser ignores it). The same variables work on #[code <ps-panel>]: set them on the element, or target #[code ps-panel] in CSS.

		+codeblock('CSS').
			[data-panel] {
				--ps-open-speed:          0.25s;        /* open transition duration */
				--ps-open-timing:         ease-in-out; /* open easing function */
				--ps-close-speed:         0.25s;        /* close transition duration */
				--ps-close-timing:        ease-in-out; /* close easing function */
				--ps-panel-width:         320px;       /* inner .panel-wrapper width (horizontal panels) */
				--ps-closed-opacity:      0;           /* opacity of .panel-wrapper when closed/closing; set to 1 to disable the fade */
			}


append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			Panel.init();
	else
		script(type="module").
			import { Panel } from 'panelset';
			Panel.init();
